1. Partition the dataset into a training set and a validation set.¶

Run a decision tree algorithm on the training set to generate a decision tree. Validate the decision tree on the validation dataset and report the total classication error (i.e. 0/1 error). Repeat the experiment with a dierent partition of training set/validation set. Plot the resulting tree. Are the resulting decision trees very dierent? Explain why.

Advice: it can be convenient to set a maximum depth for the tree.

def train_decision_tree(file_path, train_data_scale=0.8):
    '''
    TODO:
        train decision tree with special num of features
    Params:
        file_path: path of training data file
        train_data_scale: training data scale in all data
    Return:
        error value
    '''
    all_x, all_y = load_svmlight_file(file_path)
    train_x, validation_x, train_y, validation_y = train_test_split(all_x, all_y, test_size=1-train_data_scale)
    
    print('all data, train and validation shape: ', all_x.shape, all_y.shape, 
          train_x.shape, train_y.shape, validation_x.shape, validation_y.shape)
    
    model = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=10)
    
    start_time = time.time()
    model.fit(train_x, train_y) # Train the model using the training sets
    end_time = time.time()
    consume_time = end_time-start_time
    # print('consuming time: ', consume_time)
    pred_y = model.predict(validation_x)
    # print('pred_y: ', pred_y.shape)
    dot_data= export_graphviz(model, out_file=None)
    graph = graphviz.Source(dot_data) 
        
    #display(SVG(graph.pipe(format='svg')))
    display(Image(graph.pipe(format='png')))
        
    accuracy = accuracy_score(validation_y, pred_y)
    eorro_val = 1-accuracy
    print('train_data_scale:%d ', train_data_scale, 'eorro:%.2f' % eorro_val)
    return eorro_val, consume_time

train_data validation_data error
80% 20% 0.01

60% 40% 0.01

Yes, the resulting decision trees with a differnt partition of training set/validation set are very different. Because the Decision Classification Tree with CART method is used in the experiment. In CART method Gini index(Gini impurity) is a measure of how often a randomly chosen element from the set would be incorrectly labeled.The Gini impurity can be computed by summing the probability \begin{align} {\displaystyle \sum _{k\neq i}p_{k}=1-p_{i}} \end{align} of a mistake in categorizing that item. Class i in the set maybe different by partition of training set/validation set and the classificaiton is also been by different training dataset.

def train_best_svm(file_path):
    '''
    TODO:
        train the svm best parammeters with cross-validation
    Params:
        file_path: path of training data file
    Return:
    '''
    train_x, train_y = load_svmlight_file(file_path)
    print('train shape: ', train_x.shape, train_y.shape)
    
    model = SVC(class_weight='balanced')
    params_grid = {
        'C': [0.1, 1, 10],
        'gamma': [0.01, 0.1, 1],
        'kernel':['rbf'] 
    }

    start_time = time.time()
    grid_model = GridSearchCV(model, param_grid=params_grid, cv=5)
    grid_model.fit(train_x[:5000], train_y[:5000])
    
    end_time = time.time()
    consume_time = end_time-start_time
    
    print('consume_time=', consume_time)
    print('best_params_=', grid_model.best_params_)
    print('best_score_',  grid_model.best_score_, "\n")
    print('split0_test_score=', grid_model.cv_results_["split0_test_score"], "\n")
    print('split1_test_score=', grid_model.cv_results_["split1_test_score"], "\n")
    print('split2_test_score=', grid_model.cv_results_["split2_test_score"])
    return

def train_svm(file_path, C=1, gamma=1):
    '''
    TODO:
        train svm with C and gamma
    Params:
        file_path: path of training data file
    Return:
        error value
    '''
    train_x, train_y = load_svmlight_file(file_path)
    print('train shape: ', train_x.shape, train_y.shape)
    
    model = SVC(kernel='rbf', C=C, gamma=gamma)
    
    start_time = time.time()
    scores = cross_val_score(model, train_x, train_y, cv=5)
    
    end_time = time.time()
    consume_time = end_time-start_time

    print('C=', C, ' gamma=', gamma, 'consuming time=', consume_time, ' accuray=%.2f' % scores.mean())
    return scores.mean()

3. Train a Multi-Layer perceptron using the cross-entropy loss with L2 regularization (weight decay penalty).¶

In other words, the activation function equals the logistic function. Plot curves of the training and validation error as a function of the penalty strength . How do the curves behave? Explain why.

def train_multi_nn(file_path, alpha=0.0001, train_data_scale=0.7):
    '''
    TODO:
        train multi layer NN with logistic and L2 Regularization Method
    Params:
        file_path: path of training data file
        alpha: L2 penalty
    Return:
        error value
    '''
    all_x, all_y = load_svmlight_file(file_path)
    train_x, validation_x, train_y, validation_y = train_test_split(all_x, all_y, test_size=1-train_data_scale)
    
    #print('train and validation shape: ', train_x.shape, train_y.shape, validation_x.shape, validation_y.shape)
    
    model = MLPClassifier(solver='lbfgs', activation='logistic', alpha=alpha, hidden_layer_sizes=(60, 10))
    model.fit(train_x, train_y)
    
    validation_y_pred = model.predict(validation_x)
    train_y_pred = model.predict(train_x)
    
    validation_acc = accuracy_score(validation_y, validation_y_pred)
    train_acc = accuracy_score(train_y, train_y_pred)
    
    validation_error = 1-validation_acc
    train_error = 1-train_acc
    print('alpha=', alpha, 'validation_error:%.2f' % validation_error, 'train_error:%.2f' % train_error)
    return train_error, validation_error
